{
  "texts": [
    "All we need to accept to blunt this objection to P3, however, is that some genuine cognition involves intentional acts; and this is a view, at least as far as it applies to inner mental acts, attracts broad support in contemporary philosophy of mind (see, e.g., essays collected in O'Brien & Soteriou 2009).",
    "6 It is, moreover, a notable feature of this debate that at least two recent defenders of the claim that cognition can be under intentional control have also argued that making this claim either supports (Levy, 2019) or depends upon (Vierkant, 2022) the truth of something like HEC.",
    "Allowing that P2 has been rendered plausible by the previous discussion (in §2.1), it therefore might make most sense for opponents of HEC to focus on P3.",
    "To say that brain-external processes are involved in cognitive offloading is not yet to say that these constitute the cognitive act that offloading realises.",
    "Thus, the conclusion C falls short of what supporters of HEC need: the claim that human cognition is constituted by acts that themselves are constituted by processes and events beyond the bounds of the central nervous system."
  ]
}